Author-Name:  Ay&#x015F;e &#x0130;mrohoro&#x011F;lu 
Author-Name:  Selahattin &#x0130;mrohoro&#x011F;lu 
Title: Elimination of Social Security in a Dynastic Framework 
Abstract:
 Much of the existing literature on social security has taken the extreme
 assumption that individuals have little or no altruism; this paper takes
 an opposite assumption that there is full two-sided altruism. When
 households insure members that belong to the same family line, privatizing
 social security can gain public support. In our benchmark model calibrated
 to the U.S. economy, privatization without compensation is favoured by
 52&#x0025; of the population. If social security participants are fully
 compensated for their contributions, and the transition to privatization
 is financed by a combination of debt and a consumption tax, 58&#x0025;
 experience a welfare gain. These gains and the resulting public support
 for social security reform depend critically on a flexible labour market.
 If the labour supply elasticity is low, then support for privatization
 disappears.  Copyright 2007, Wiley-Blackwell.
