Author-Name:  Felix Kubler 
Title: Verifying Competitive Equilibria in Dynamic Economies 
Abstract:
 In this paper, I examine &epsiv;-equilibria of stationary dynamic
 economies with heterogeneous agents and possibly incomplete financial
 markets. I give a simple example to show that even for arbitrarily small
 &epsiv; &gt; 0, allocation and prices can be far away from exact
 equilibrium allocations and prices. That is, errors in market clearing or
 individuals' optimality conditions do not provide enough information to
 assess the quality of an approximation. I derive a sufficient condition
 for an &epsiv;-equilibrium to be close to an exact equilibrium. If the
 economic fundamentals are semi-algebraic, one can verify computationally
 whether this condition holds. The condition can be interpreted
 economically as a robustness requirement on the set of &epsiv;-equilibria
 which form a neighbourhood of the computed approximation. I illustrate the
 main result and the computational method using an infinite horizon economy
 with overlapping generations and incomplete financial markets.  Copyright 2011, Oxford University Press.
