Author-Name:  Pushkar Maitra 
Title: Social Learning and Norms in a Public Goods Experiment with Inter-Generational Advice<xref ref-type="fn" rid="FN1">-super-1</xref> 
Abstract:
 We study a linear public goods game using an inter-generational approach.
 Subjects in one generation leave advice for the succeeding generation via
 free-form messages. Such advice can be private knowledge (advice left by
 one player in generation t is given only to his or her immediate successor
 in generation t &#x002B; 1), public knowledge (advice left by players of
 generation t is made available to all members of generation t &#x002B; 1),
 and common knowledge (where the advice is not only public but is also read
 aloud by the experimenter). Common knowledge of advice generates a process
 of social learning that leads to high contributions and less free-riding.
 This behaviour is sustained by advice that is generally exhortative,
 suggesting high contributions, which in turn creates optimistic beliefs
 among subjects about others' contributions. We suggest that socially
 connected communities may achieve high contributions to a public good even
 in the absence of punishment for norm violators.  Copyright 2006, Wiley-Blackwell.
