Author-Name:  Ulrich Doraszelski 
Author-Name:  Jordi Jaumandreu 
Title: R&D and Productivity: Estimating Endogenous Productivity 
Abstract:
 We develop a model of endogenous productivity change to examine the impact
 of the investment in knowledge on the productivity of firms. Our dynamic
 investment model extends the tradition of the knowledge capital model of
 <xref ref-type="bibr" rid="B30">Griliches (1979)</xref> that has remained
 a cornerstone of the productivity literature. Rather than constructing a
 stock of knowledge capital from a firm's observed R&D expenditures, we
 consider productivity to be unobservable to the econometrician. Our
 approach accounts for uncertainty, non-linearity, and heterogeneity across
 firms in the link between R&D and productivity. We also derive a novel
 estimator for production functions in this setting. Using an unbalanced
 panel of more than 1800 Spanish manufacturing firms in nine industries
 during the 1990s, we provide evidence of non-linearities as well as
 economically significant uncertainties in the R&D process. R&D
 expenditures play a key role in determining the differences in
 productivity across firms and the evolution of firm-level productivity
 over time.  Copyright 2013, Oxford University Press.
