Author-Name:  Christopher J. Flinn
Title: Labour Market Structure and Inequality: A Comparison of Italy and the U.S. 
Abstract:
 Markets with rigid labour regulations and centralized wage setting are
 often thought to be inefficient but egalitarian. Using a model of off- and
 on-the-job search and event-history, individual-level data for Italy and
 the U.S., we show that while the cross-sectional wage distributions of
 young Italian males are much more compressed than are the comparable
 distributions for young white U.S. males, the estimated search model
 implies that the distribution of lifetime welfare is no more disperse in
 the U.S. than it is in Italy. Our model implies that the high frequency of
 movements between labour market states leads to both a relatively
 equitable distribution of "long run" welfare in the U.S. and a high level
 of cross-sectional inequality.  Copyright 2002, Wiley-Blackwell.
