Author-Name:  Daniel Diermeier 
Author-Name:  Razvan Vlaicu 
Title: Executive Control and Legislative Success 
Abstract:
 The higher legislative success of parliamentary governments relative to
 presidential governments has been used to argue that legislative success
 is driven by parliamentary governments' superior agenda power or their
 control of legislative majorities. We show that this approach is at odds
 with some of the empirical regularities across and within political
 systems. We then propose a legislative bargaining model to elucidate this
 puzzle. In the model, the policies of a confidence-dependent parliamentary
 government enjoy more predictable support from governing coalition members
 because their short-term policy goals are less important than the
 government's survival. Coalition support is stronger when the government
 has more agenda power and is weaker with a larger ruling coalition. We
 explore the empirical implications of these findings and their
 consequences for the comparative study of legislative institutions.  Copyright 2011, Oxford University Press.
