Author-Name:  Ben Lockwood
Title: Distributive Politics and the Costs of Centralization 
Abstract:
 This paper studies the choice between centralization and decentralization
 of fiscal policy in a political economy setting. With centralization,
 regional delegates vote over agendas comprising sets of region-specific
 projects. The outcome is inefficient because the choice of projects is
 insufficiently sensitive to within-region benefits. The number of projects
 funded may be non-monotonic in the strength of project externalities. The
 efficiency gains from decentralization, and the performance of
 &#x201C;constitutional rules&#x201D; (such as majority voting) which may
 be used to choose between decentralization and centralization, are then
 discussed in this framework. Weaker externalities and more heterogeneity
 between regions need not increase the efficiency gain from
 decentralization.  Copyright 2002, Wiley-Blackwell.
