Title: Time-Consistent Public Policy 
Abstract:
 In this paper we study how a benevolent government that cannot commit to
 future policy should trade off the costs and benefits of public
 expenditure. We characterize and solve for Markov-perfect equilibria of
 the dynamic game between successive governments. The characterization
 consists of an inter-temporal first-order condition (a "generalized Euler
 equation") for the government, and we use it both to gain insight into the
 nature of the equilibrium and as a basis for computations. For a
 calibrated economy, we find that when the only tax base available to the
 government is capital income&#x02014;an inelastic source of funds at any
 point in time&#x02014;the government still refrains from taxing at
 confiscatory rates. We also find that when the only tax base is labour
 income the Markov equilibrium features less public expenditure and lower
 tax rates than the Ramsey equilibrium.  Copyright 2008, Wiley-Blackwell.
