Author-Name:  Michael J. Pries
Title: Persistence of Employment Fluctuations: A Model of Recurring Job Loss 
Abstract:
 Standard models of employment fluctuations cannot reconcile the
 unemployment rate's remarkable persistence with the high job-finding rates
 found in worker flows data. A matching model emphasizing high hazard rates
 among newly formed firm-worker matches can resolve this shortcoming. In
 the model, matches are experience goods; consequently, newly employed
 workers face higher hazard rates. Following a job loss, workers may
 experience several short-lived jobs before finding stable employment. At
 an aggregate level, an initial burst of job loss precipitates a steady
 flow of recurring job loss. A simulation shows that this recurring job
 loss can account for the fact that the unemployment rate remains elevated
 for as much as 4 or 5 years following an initial jump.  Copyright 2004, Wiley-Blackwell.
