Author-Name:  J. Duggan 
Author-Name:  C. Martinelli 
Title: A Spatial Theory of Media Slant and Voter Choice 
Abstract:
 We develop a theory of media slant as a systematic filtering of political
 news that reduces multidimensional politics to the one-dimensional space
 perceived by voters. Economic and political choices are interdependent in
 our theory: expected electoral results influence economic choices, and
 economic choices in turn influence voting behaviour. In a two-candidate
 election, we show that media favouring the front-runner will focus on
 issues unlikely to deliver a surprise, while media favouring the underdog
 will gamble for resurrection. We characterize the socially optimal slant
 and show that it coincides with the one favoured by the underdog under a
 variety of circumstances. Balanced media, giving each issue equal
 coverage, may be worse for voters than partisan media.  Copyright 2011, Oxford University Press.
