Title: Persistent Inequality 
Abstract:
 When human capital accumulation generates pecuniary externalities across
 professions, and capital markets are imperfect, persistent inequality in
 utility and consumption is inevitable in any steady state. This is true
 irrespective of the degree of divisibility in investments. However,
 divisibility (or fineness of occupational structure) has implications for
 both the multiplicity and Pareto-efficiency of steady states.
 Indivisibilities generate a continuum of inefficient and efficient steady
 states with varying per capita income. On the other hand, perfect
 divisibility typically implies the existence of a unique steady state
 distribution which is Pareto-efficient.  Copyright 2003, Wiley-Blackwell.
