Author-Name:  Zhihao Yu
Title: Environmental Protection: A Theory of Direct and Indirect Competition for Political Influence 
Abstract:
 How is it that environmental groups can have a strong impact on
 environmental policy but without much lobbying? This paper develops a
 model of "direct" (lobbying the government) and "indirect" (persuading the
 public) competition for political influence and finds that they are
 complementary. However, an increase in the effectiveness of public
 persuasion, or a rise of public environmental awareness, induces
 substitution between the two. The findings establish that the empirical
 phenomenon of lack of political contribution from environmental groups may
 not be related to financial constraints, but to their greater
 effectiveness in public persuasion and growing public environmental
 awareness.  Copyright 2005, Wiley-Blackwell.
