Title: Consideration Sets and Competitive Marketing 
Abstract:
 We study a market model in which competing firms use costly marketing
 devices to influence the set of alternatives which consumers perceive as
 relevant. Consumers in our model are boundedly rational in the sense that
 they have an imperfect perception of what is relevant to their decision
 problem. They apply well-defined preferences to a "consideration set",
 which is a function of the marketing devices employed by the firms. We
 examine the implications of this behavioural model in the context of a
 competitive market model, particularly on industry profits, vertical
 product differentiation, the use of marketing devices, and consumers'
 conversion rates.  Copyright 2011, Oxford University Press.
