Author-Name:  Mattias K. Polborn 
Title: Voting on Majority Rules 
Abstract:
 We analyse an overlapping generations model of voting on "reform
 projects". These resemble investments in that they first require some
 investment expenditure and later payoff. Since the time during which old
 people get the benefit is shorter, or because older people are more
 wealthy and hence pay more taxes, they are more conservative (against
 reforms) than young people.We show that if people vote on which majority
 should be required in future elections for a bill to become a law, the
 winning proposal specifies a supermajority. This result is very robust
 even if age related conflict is only one determinant among others for
 voting behaviour in the society.  Copyright 2004, Wiley-Blackwell.
