Title: Housing Liquidity, Mobility, and the Labour Market 
Abstract:
 We study the interactions among geographical mobility, unemployment, and
 home-ownership in an economy with heterogeneous locations, endogenous
 construction, and search frictions in the markets for both labour and
 housing. The decision of home-owners to accept job offers from other
 cities depends on how quickly they can sell their houses (i.e. the houses'
 liquidity), which in turn depends on local labour market conditions.
 Consequently, home-owners accept job offers from other cities at a lower
 rate than do renters, generating a link between home-ownership and
 unemployment both at the city level and in the aggregate. When calibrated
 to match aggregate U.S. statistics on mobility, housing, and labour flows,
 the model predicts that the effect of home-ownership on aggregate
 unemployment is small. When unemployment is high, however, changes in the
 rate of home-ownership can have economically significant effects.  Copyright , Oxford University Press.
