Title: Social Preferences, Skill Segregation, and Wage Dynamics 
Abstract:
 We study the earning structure and the equilibrium assignment of workers
 to firms in a model in which workers have social preferences, and skills
 are perfectly substitutable in production. Firms offer long-term
 contracts, and we allow for frictions in the labour market in the form of
 mobility costs. The model delivers specific predictions about the nature
 of worker flows, about the characteristics of workplace skill segregation,
 and about wage dispersion both within and across firms. We show that
 long-term contracts in the presence of social preferences associate
 within-firm wage dispersion with novel "internal labour market" features
 such as gradual promotions, productivity-unrelated wage increases, and
 downward wage flexibility. These three dynamic features lead to
 productivity-unrelated wage volatility within firms.  Copyright 2008, Wiley-Blackwell.
