Title: Optimal Indirect and Capital Taxation 
Abstract:
 We consider an environment in which agents' skills are private information
 and follow arbitrary stochastic processes. We prove that it is typically
 Pareto optimal for an individual's marginal benefit of investing in
 capital to exceed his marginal cost of doing so. This wedge is consistent
 with a positive tax on capital income. We also prove that it is Pareto
 optimal for the marginal rate of substitution between any two consumption
 goods to equal the marginal rate of transformation. This lack of a wedge
 is consistent with uniform taxation of consumption goods within a period.  Copyright 2003, Wiley-Blackwell.
