Author-Name:  Asher Wolinsky 
Title: Second Opinions and Price Competition: Inefficiency in the Market for Expert Advice 
Abstract:
 We consider a market in which an expert must exert costly but unobservable
 effort to identify the service that meets the consumer's need. In our
 model, experts offer competing contracts and the consumer may gather
 multiple opinions. We explore the incentives that a competitive sampling
 of prices and opinions provides for experts to exert effort and find that
 there is a tension between price competition and the equilibrium effort.
 In particular, the equilibrium fails to realize the second best welfare
 optimum. An intervention, that limits price competition via price control,
 increases welfare.  Copyright 2003, Wiley-Blackwell.
