Author-Name:  Marcin P&eogon;ski 
Title: Critical Types 
Abstract:
 How can we know in advance whether simplifying assumptions about beliefs
 will make a difference in the conclusions of game-theoretic models? We
 define critical types to be types whose rationalizable correspondence is
 sensitive to assumptions about arbitrarily high-order beliefs. We show
 that a type is critical if and only if it exhibits common belief in some
 non-trivial event. We use this characterization to show that all types in
 commonly used type spaces are critical. On the other hand, we show that
 regular types (types that are not critical) are generic, although perhaps
 inconvenient to use in applications.  Copyright 2011, Oxford University Press.
