Author-Name:  Jo&atilde;o M. P. De Mello 
Title: Campaign Advertising and Election Outcomes: Quasi-natural Experiment Evidence from Gubernatorial Elections in Brazil 
Abstract:
 Whether campaign advertising influences election outcomes is an open
 question; a paradox given the amount spent on campaigning in general and
 TV advertising in particular. We argue that such "absence of
 documentation" is due to the focus of the empirical literature on the
 U.S., where the allocation of campaign spending and advertising is
 decentralized. We explore a quasi-natural experiment that enables us to
 mitigate the omitted variables and reverse causality problems caused by
 decentralized allocation. In Brazil, gubernatorial elections work in a
 two-round system. In the first round, candidates' TV time shares are
 determined by their coalitions' share of seats in the National Parliament.
 In the second round, TV time is split equally between the first-round
 winner and runner-up. Using differences between rounds as a source of
 variation, we find a large causal effect of TV advertising on election
 outcomes.  Copyright 2011, Oxford University Press.
