Title: Using Stock Price Information to Regulate Firms 
Abstract:
 This paper examines the role of the information contained in stock prices
 in the regulation of privatized firms. Stock prices contain noisy but
 unbiased information about firm's future prospects that regulators can use
 to decide on some regulatory policies. The main argument developed is that
 the observation of stock price movements reduces the incentives of
 regulators to develop their own monitoring technologies and can allow them
 to commit to relatively lighthanded regulations. This protects firm's
 investments in cost reduction activities and can increase ex ante welfare.  Copyright 2002, Wiley-Blackwell.
