Title: Collusion, Exclusion, and Inclusion in Random-Order Bargaining 
Abstract:
 This paper examines the profitability of three types of integration in a
 cooperative game solved by a random-order value (e.g. the Shapley value).
 Collusion between players i and j is a contract merging their resources in
 the hands of one of them, say i. This contract can be represented as a
 combination of exclusion, which lets i exclude j's resource but not use it
 himself, and inclusion, which lets i use j's resource but not exclude j
 from it. This representation yields a third-difference condition on the
 characteristic function that determines the profitability of collusion,
 generalizing existing results for specific games. Namely, collusion is
 profitable [unprofitable] when the complementarity of the colluding
 players is reduced [increased] by other players.  Copyright 2003, Wiley-Blackwell.
