Title: Identification of Search Models using Record Statistics 
Abstract:
 This paper shows how record-value theory, a branch of statistics that
 deals with the timing and magnitude of extreme values in sequences of
 random variables, can be used to recover features of the wage offer
 distribution in conventional search models. Using National Longitudinal
 Survey of Youth (NLSY) wage data, I show that the data are not compatible
 with specifications for the offer distribution characterized by extreme
 negative skewness. In addition, I show that my approach can be used to
 construct a bound on the returns to job seniority. My results suggest that
 job seniority plays only a minor role in the wage growth of the workers
 surveyed in the NLSY.  Copyright 2008, Wiley-Blackwell.
