Title: Nonparametric Estimation of Sample Selection Models 
Abstract:
 Sample selection models provide an important way of accounting for
 economic decisions that combine discrete and continuous choices and of
 correcting for nonrandom sampling. Nonparametric estimators for these
 models are developed in this paper. These can be used for estimating
 shapes and important economic quantities, as in standard nonparametric
 regression. Endogeneity of regressors of interest is allowed for. Series
 estimators for these models are developed, which are useful for imposing
 additivity restrictions that arise from selection corrections. Convergence
 rates and asymptotic normality results are derived. An application to
 returns to schooling among Australian young females is given.  Copyright 2003, Wiley-Blackwell.
