Author-Name:  V. V Chari
Author-Name:  Patrick J. Kehoe 
Author-Name:  Ellen R. McGrattan 
Title: Can Sticky Price Models Generate Volatile and Persistent Real Exchange Rates? 
Abstract:
 The central puzzle in international business cycles is that fluctuations
 in real exchange rates are volatile and persistent. We quantify the
 popular story for real exchange rate fluctuations: they are generated by
 monetary shocks interacting with sticky goods prices. If prices are held
 fixed for at least one year, risk aversion is high, and preferences are
 separable in leisure, then real exchange rates generated by the model are
 as volatile as in the data and quite persistent, but less so than in the
 data. The main discrepancy between the model and the data, the
 consumption&#x2014;real exchange rate anomaly, is that the model generates
 a high correlation between real exchange rates and the ratio of
 consumption across countries, while the data show no clear pattern between
 these variables.  Copyright 2002, Wiley-Blackwell.
