Title: Robust Predictions in Infinite-Horizon Games--an Unrefinable Folk Theorem 
Abstract:
 We show that in any game that is continuous at infinity, if a plan of
 action a<sub>i</sub> is played by a type t<sub>i</sub> in a Bayesian Nash
 equilibrium, then there are perturbations of t<sub>i</sub> for which
 a<sub>i</sub> is the only rationalizable plan and whose unique
 rationalizable belief regarding the play of the game is arbitrarily close
 to the equilibrium belief of t<sub>i</sub>. As an application to repeated
 games, we prove an unrefinable folk theorem: any individually rational and
 feasible payoff is the unique rationalizable payoff vector for some
 perturbed type profile. This is true even if perturbed types are
 restricted to believe that the repeated-game payoff structure and the
 discount factor are common knowledge.  Copyright , Oxford University Press.
