Author-Name:  David S. Ahn
Title: Ambiguity Without a State Space 
Abstract:
 Many decisions involve both imprecise probabilities and intractable states
 of the world. Objective expected utility assumes unambiguous
 probabilities; subjective expected utility assumes a completely specified
 state space. This paper analyses a third domain of preference: sets of
 consequential lotteries. Using this domain, we develop a theory of
 objective ambiguity without explicit reference to any state space. We
 characterize a representation that integrates a non-linear transformation
 of first-order expected utility with respect to a second-order measure.
 The concavity of the transformation and the weighting of the measure
 capture ambiguity aversion. We propose a definition for comparative
 ambiguity aversion.  Copyright 2008, Wiley-Blackwell.
