Title: Market Provision of Broadcasting: A Welfare Analysis 
Abstract:
 This paper presents a theory of the market provision of broadcasting and
 uses it to address the nature of market failure in the industry.
 Equilibrium advertising levels may be too low or too high, depending on
 the nuisance cost to viewers, the substitutability of programmes, and the
 expected benefits to advertisers from contacting viewers. The equilibrium
 amount of programming may also be below or above the socially optimal
 level. Perhaps surprisingly, the ability to price programming may reduce
 social surplus, while monopoly ownership may increase it.  Copyright 2005, Wiley-Blackwell.
