Title: Inefficient Credit Booms 
Abstract:
 This paper studies the welfare properties of competitive equilibria in an
 economy with financial frictions hit by aggregate shocks. In particular,
 it shows that competitive financial contracts can result in excessive
 borrowing ex ante and excessive volatility ex post. Even though from a
 first-best perspective the equilibrium always displays under-borrowing,
 from a second-best point of view excessive borrowing can arise. The
 inefficiency is due to the combination of limited commitment in financial
 contracts and the fact that asset prices are determined in a spot market.
 This generates a pecuniary externality that is not internalized in private
 contracts. The model provides a framework to evaluate preventive policies,
 which can be used during a credit boom to reduce the expected costs of a
 financial crisis.  Copyright 2008, Wiley-Blackwell.
