Title: Arms Races and Negotiations 
Abstract:
 Two players simultaneously decide whether or not to acquire new weapons in
 an arms race game. Each player's type determines his propensity to arm.
 Types are private information, and are independently drawn from a
 continuous distribution. With probability close to one, the best outcome
 for each player is for neither to acquire new weapons (although each
 prefers to acquire new weapons if he thinks the opponent will). There is a
 small probability that a player is a dominant strategy type who always
 prefers to acquire new weapons. We find conditions under which the unique
 Bayesian-Nash equilibrium involves an arms race with probability one.
 However, if the probability that a player is a dominant strategy type is
 sufficiently small, then there is an equilibrium of the cheap-talk
 extension of the game where the probability of an arms race is close to
 zero.  Copyright 2004, Wiley-Blackwell.
