Title: On Price Caps Under Uncertainty 
Abstract:
 This paper shows how standard arguments supporting the imposition of price
 caps break down in the presence of demand uncertainty. In particular,
 though in the deterministic case the introduction or lowering of a price
 cap (above marginal cost) results in increased production, increased total
 welfare, decreased prices, and increased consumer welfare, we show that
 all of the above comparative statics predictions fail for generic
 uncertain demand functions. For example, for price caps sufficiently close
 to marginal cost, a decrease in the price cap always leads to a decrease
 in production and total welfare under certain mild conditions. Under
 stronger regularity assumptions, all of the monotone comparative statics
 predictions from the deterministic case also do not hold for a generic
 uncertain demand if we restrict attention to price caps in an arbitrary
 fixed interval (as long as the price caps are binding for some values in
 that interval).  Copyright 2007, Wiley-Blackwell.
