Author-Name:  Matteo Bobba 
Title: Liquidity, Risk, and Occupational Choices 
Abstract:
 We explore which financial constraints matter most in the choice of
 becoming an entrepreneur. We consider a randomly assigned welfare
 programme in rural Mexico and show that cash transfers significantly
 increase entry into entrepreneurship. We then exploit cross-household
 variation in the timing of these transfers and find that current
 occupational choices are significantly more responsive to the transfers
 expected for the future than to those currently received. Guided by a
 simple occupational choice model, we argue that the programme has promoted
 entrepreneurship by enhancing willingness to bear risk as opposed to
 simply relaxing current liquidity constraints.  Copyright 2013, Oxford University Press.
