Author-Name:  Francesco Avvisati 
Author-Name:  Marc Gurgand 
Author-Name:  Nina Guyon 
Author-Name:  Eric Maurin 
Title: Getting Parents Involved: A Field Experiment in Deprived Schools 
Abstract:
 This article provides evidence that schools can influence parents'
 involvement in education, and this has causal effects on pupils'
 behaviour. Furthermore, it shows how the impact of more involved parents
 on their children is amplified at the class level by peer group
 interaction. We build on a large-scale controlled experiment run in a
 French deprived educational district, where parents of middle-school
 children were invited to participate in a simple program of parent--school
 meetings on how to get better involved in their children's education. At
 the end of the school year, we find that treated families have increased
 their school-and home-based involvement activities. In turn, pupils of
 treatment classes have developed more positive behaviour and attitudes in
 school, notably in terms of truancy and disciplinary sanctions (with
 effects-size around 15% of a standard deviation). However, test scores did
 not improve under the intervention. Our results suggest that parents are
 an input for schooling policies and it is possible to influence important
 aspects of the schooling process at low cost.  Copyright 2014, Oxford University Press.
