Title: The Concept of Income in a General Equilibrium 
Abstract:
 This paper derives a concept of aggregate real income for a competitive
 economy in general equilibrium consisting of heterogeneous infinitely
 lived people and relates it to current and future consumption
 possibilities. An important characteristic of our measure of income, which
 we call Real Income, is that deflation is carried out using a consumption
 deflator rather than any price index of output. We suggest that it may be
 inappropriate to regard capital gains as income. We also present a
 coherent treatment of the effects of changes to the terms of trade on Real
 Income and explain the implications of this for resource-exporting
 economies.  Copyright 2006, Wiley-Blackwell.
